Concatenate keys in a nested dict, e.g.:
        >>> d = {'a': {'b': 1, 'c': 2}, 'd': 3}
        >>> dict(concat_keys(d))
        {'a.b': 1, 'a.c': 2, 'd': 3}
Special when values is a list:
        >>> d = {'a': {'b': 1, 'c': 2}, 'd': [3, {'e': 4}]}
        >>> dict(concat_keys(d))
        {'a.b': 1, 'a.c': 2, 'd.0': 3, 'd.1.e': 4}
Args:
    d: dict
    sep: separator between keys
Returns:
    generator of (key, value) pairs
